\lang1033\b\f1\fs16 White to play\lang1042\b0\f0\fs18
\lang1033\f1\fs16 Black has just played the marked stone in an attempt to make life.  It doesn't work.  Find White's response.  The best result is a pae.

\lang1042\f0\fs18
])
(;AW[qn][ro][pp][qp][pq][nr][or]AB[rp][qq][rq][pr][os][qs]LB[sp:B][rs:A]
;W[rr]
;B[sr]LB[rr:1][sr:2][sp:B][rs:A]C[Dia.1 Matbogi

A common mistake you will see in real games is White 1.  It looks like it's on the right spot.  But when Black plays 2, now A and B are matbogi, meaning when White plays A, Black will play B, and vice versa.

\lang1042\f1\fs18

])
(;AW[qn][ro][pp][qp][pq][nr][or]AB[rp][qq][rq][pr][os][qs]
;W[ns]
;B[sr]
;W[sp]
;B[rs]LB[ns:1][sr:2][sp:3][rs:4]C[Dia.2 Bad reading

Coming from the outside with 1 in an attempt to make a Pae is bad reading.  Black 2 is the response to White 1.  When White plays at 3 to get rid of that eye Black will play 4 and make two eyes easily.
\lang1042\f1\fs18

])
(;AW[qn][ro][pp][qp][pq][nr][or]AB[rp][qq][rq][pr][os][qs]
;W[sr]
;B[rr]
;W[ns]
;B[ps]
;W[rs]LB[sr:1][rr:2][ns:3][ps:4][rs:5]C[Dia.3 Correct / Pae is the best result

White should start off with the placement attack of 1.  Now White 3 has some meaning.  When Black connects to maintain his eye White can throw in with 5 and then we have a Pae.  This is the best result.
\lang1042\f1\fs18

